Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as a twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member state of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had begun working closely with the ESA in 1994 and over the years that followed participated in a number of projects of the agency.
The road to Poland into space, however, began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, Poles passionate worked on space flights; they did not meet always understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the conference A. Šternfeld the astronomical observatory in Warsaw on December 6, 1933, during which he presented ideas from his book avant-garde entitled "introduction to cosmonautics."
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left listeners cold and years later Šternfeld recalled that only Dr Jan Gadomski was attracted to its work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for his book "introduction to cosmonautics."
The doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) became a great propagator of astronomy and space travel.
He published hundreds of articles in the Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of cosmonautics of world renown, his contribution has been rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters of the Far Side of the Moon.
From 1925 was built in Poland a speeder intended to be equipped with a rocket engine.
The problem is that neither the author nor the details of this project.
It is not clear whether the rocket would be used to propel or curb the speeder.
The only information known about this speeder are those of the press at the time.
From 1933, the Polish artillery began to devote themselves to rockets.
The search was conducted by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with teachers Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It is clear from the documents kept that research had reached the trial stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, research stalled.
In 1937, plans a rocket hunting photoelectric, designed by the engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" an author called Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
These two projects were directed a military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects using the technique of rockets were conducted by the provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), who coordinated all work.
The council was created in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other work on the aircraft were published in the Polish press, thanks to astronavigation Polish society (our Polskie Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is a question of a society in the November issue of 1954's Problem newspaper, in which four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Mr. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society devoted to astronavigation
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had for the future.
At the beginning of the year 1956, Polish society astronavigation (PTA) deployed efforts to enter the International Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and in the autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He retained his position until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the ATP brought a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM (Rakieta weather rocket Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 metres had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently was built an improved version, RM-1A, and during the summer of 1959, flight tests of the rocket two-storey MR-2 were launched in the desert Bledov.
The rocket had a length of 1.4 metres and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The prototype should have been able to make concrete scientific work - MR rocket-34 ought to have a range of up to 14.5 km and serve to observe the wind aloft.
But in 1963, all development work was halted.
The Meteor rocket-1 development during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first type of rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, 1B and --1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 litre, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 per litre and Meteor-1C 0.62 per litre.
The maximum scope of all of these types of gear was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first test flight began in October 1970.
The Meteor rocket-2 had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently were built the Meteor-2H versions and Meteor-3.
It is still necessary to mention the entry of Poland to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national committee COSPAR two years later.
Under the program Interkosmos, Poland has also participated in space exploration on the Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimir Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this programme.
