The situation did not offer to the American administration of positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have severely shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, she was able to obtain the release of the hostages.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, compounded later by the fiasco of the attempt to release of the hostages by force.
Diplomats kidnapped were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate provoked in the United States a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iranian sentiment.
The Iranian debacle contributed strongly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter with Ronald Reagan in the presidential elections in 1980.
